  "prompt": "Were humans ever subject to natural selection?",
  "response": "Yes, humans have been and continue to be subject to natural selection. Throughout human history, environmental pressures, diseases, climate changes, and other factors have influenced human survival and reproduction. Some examples include:\n\n1. Genetic adaptations to different environments:\n- Skin color variations\n- High-altitude adaptations in populations like Tibetans\n- Lactose tolerance in populations with dairy farming history\n\n2. Disease resistance:\n- Sickle cell trait providing resistance to malaria\n- Genetic variations that offer protection against certain infectious diseases\n\n3. Historical survival challenges:\n- Climate variations\n- Food availability\n- Predation\n- Conflicts between populations\n\n4. Modern natural selection:\n- Genetic factors influencing disease susceptibility\n- Reproductive success rates\n- Genetic variations affecting fertility\n\nWhile modern medical technologies and social structures have reduced some traditional selection pressures, natural selection still operates on human populations, though potentially at a slower rate than in prehistoric times.\n\nThe process continues today, with genetic variations that enhance survival and reproductive success having a higher likelihood of being passed to future generations.",
